  "why": "The paper explicitly identifies input fidelity (preserving semantics and naturalness) as a core requirement and designs a specific component to enforce it throughout the fuzzing process. The proposed method, DRFuzz, uses a \"GAN-based Fidelity Assurance\" technique. This involves training a GAN discriminator on the original dataset to learn the distribution of natural, plausible inputs. During fuzzing, every generated mutant is passed through this discriminator, which acts as a filter. Only inputs that the discriminator classifies as realistic (i.e., resembling the learned distribution) are kept for further processing and potential inclusion in the seed pool. This mechanism directly addresses the metric's \"High\" criteria by \"restricting search to a learned plausible distribution\" and is designed to prevent the cumulative distortion that can occur across many mutation iterations, rather than just controlling similarity between successive steps. The paper's ablation study empirically demonstrates that this GAN-based component effectively filters out a significant percentage of low-fidelity inputs.",
